no-bitwise.description:
Description

This rule disallows bitwise operators.

Examples ofincorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint no-bitwise: "error"*/

let x = y | z;

const x1 = y & z;

const x2 = y ^ z;

const x3 = ~ z;

const x4 = y << z;

const x5 = y >> z;

const x6 = y >>> z;

x |= y;

x &= y;

x ^= y;

x <<= y;

x >>= y;

x >>>= y;

Examples ofcorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint no-bitwise: "error"*/

let x = y || z;

const x1 = y && z;

const x2 = y > z;

const x3 = y < z;

x += y;

no-bitwise.option:
This rule has an object option:

- "allow": Allows a list of bitwise operators to be used as exceptions.
- "int32Hint": Allows the use of bitwise OR in|0pattern for type casting.

allow

Examples ofcorrectcode for this rule with the{ "allow": ["~"] }option:

/*eslint no-bitwise: ["error", { "allow": ["~"] }] */

~[1,2,3].indexOf(1) === -1;

int32Hint

Examples ofcorrectcode for this rule with the{ "int32Hint": true }option:

/*eslint no-bitwise: ["error", { "int32Hint": true }] */

const b = a|0;
